      "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
      "body": "Would it make sense to include an extreme transaction with lots of inputs (similar to this: https://www.blockchain.com/btc/tx/bb41a757f405890fb0f5856228e23b715702d714d59bf2b1feb70d8b2b4e3e08 further explanation here: http://rusty.ozlabs.org/?p=522) for this benchmark, to compare legacy vs BIP 143 signature hash performance? Though I can hardly imagine that it was not done in the course of the introduction of BIP 143, as runtime reduction from O(n²) to O(n) was one of the main points of this. Or is this indirectly tested with some other benchmarks? If yes, what's the point of having separate benchmarks focussing on solely the signature hash? Just asking all this from the perspective of a newbie.",
